TY  - JOUR
TI  - Comparison of Single-Lumen Midline Catheters to Long Peripheral Intravenous Lines in the Emergency Department: a Randomized Controlled Trial
AU  - Bracey, A
AU  - Schaefer, E
AU  - Chang, AK
AU  - Brecheisen, J
AU  - Ahmed, S
AU  - Ata, A
AU  - Aly, I
AU  - Mantas, J
AU  - Hayashi, W
AU  - Leavitt, R
AU  - Diaz, S
AU  - Von Dollen, W
AU  - Pauze, DR
AU  - Waxman, MJ
JO  - Academic emergency medicine
AB  - Background and Objectives: Achieving intravenous (IV) access in ED patients may be challenging. Prior work has demonstrated that 1‐in‐ 9 ED patients may have difficult IV access, which has been associated with morbidity due to delays in diagnostic testing, treatment, and ED length of stay. Recently, midline catheters (MCs) have gained popularity for patients with difficult IV access. We hypothesized that MCs have increased dwell time over US‐guided long PIV (US‐PIV) in patients with difficult IV access presenting to the ED. Methods: We performed a preliminary analysis of a single center, prospective, 2‐arm, nonblinded, randomized clinical trial to determine if ultrasound‐guided 10‐cm single‐lumen midline catheters (US‐MCs) have longer dwell times compared to ultrasound‐guided 4.78‐cm peripheral intravenous catheters (US‐PIVs) in a convenience sample of patients with difficult IV access presenting to the ED. The study setting was a large, urban, academic, tertiary care center enrolling eligible patients since October 2024. The primary outcome was dwell‐time of each type of catheter. Secondary outcomes included rates of complications and completion of care. Demographic and clinical data were also collected. Statistical analysis was performed using descriptive analytics and p‐values were calculated by student's t‐test. Results: Twenty patients were enrolled during the study period (US‐MC group n = 10 and US‐PIV group n = 10). The median (IQR) age was 55 (39‐67) years,62% (13/21) of patients were female, and 62% (13/21) were white/Caucasian. Of all patients, 71% (15/21) were considered «high‐risk» by ED Difficult IV Access score. The mean (standard deviation [SD]) dwell times of US‐MC and US‐PIVs were 49 (84) and 20 (21) h respectively (p = 0.3). Of all patients, 42% (9/21) were admitted to the hospital, among which the mean dwell‐time for US‐MC and US‐PIVs was 68 (107) and 37 (31) h respectively (p = 0.6). Only one complication (dislodgement) was reported in one patient in the US‐MC cohort. All other vascular access devices were functional until completion of care. Conclusion: The preliminary analysis of this ongoing study demonstrates that US‐MCs may have similar dwell‐times and complication rates compared to US‐PIVs in those with difficult IV presenting to the ED.
