AB  - INTERVENTION: Along the visual axis (AL) group,Across the visual axis (AC) group Experimental Procedure/Surgery,Active Comparator Procedure/Surgery The needle insertion is parallel to the operator&amp;#039;s visual axis and perpendicular to the US screen,The needle insertion is perpendicular to the operator&amp;#039;s visual axis and parallel to the US screen CONDITION: Peripheral intravenous cannulation in surgical patients Ultrasound‐guided vascular access procedures Procedural ergonomics in IV access under ultrasound guidance ; Peripheral IV cannulation ; Ultrasound guidance vascular access; Needle alignment and the visual axis; Ergonomics Peripheral IV cannulation ; Ultrasound guidance vascular access; Needle alignment and the visual axis; Ergonomics PRIMARY OUTCOME: Time to successful cannulation From needle skin puncture to successful catheter advancement confirmed by blood flashback and 10‐mL of normal saline injection without any signs of inflitration Duration in seconds through video recording of the procedure assessment SECONDARY OUTCOME: First attempt success rate Immediate after the successful cannulation Percentage,Number of attempts Immediate after the successful cannulation Number of needle‐skin contact,Procedure‐related complications within 24 hours (e.g., leakage, dislodgement, nerve injury, phlebitis) Within 24 hours after the procedure Number,Patient pain score Immediate after the successful cannulation NRS score 0‐10,Patient satisfaction Immediate after the successful cannulation Likert score 1‐5,Operator&amp;#039;s musculoskeletal symptom risks Immediate after the procedure Questionnaire interview INCLUSION CRITERIA: 1) Adults aged 18 ‐ 80 years 2) Undergoing elective or emergency surgery requiring peripheral IV access before anesthesia
