TY  - JOUR
TI  - EFFICACY OF PIVC INSERTION USING IMAGING TECHNOLOGY COMPARED TO COMBINED PALPATION AND VISUALIZATION. THE EPIC RANDOMISED CONTROLLED TRIAL
AU  - Kleidon, T
AU  - Schults, J
AU  - Rickard, C
AU  - Ullman, A
JO  - Journal of vascular access
AB  - Background: Peripheral intravenous catheter (PIVC) insertion can be difficult, traumatic, and time‐consuming in paediatric patients. Children with difficult intravenous access (DIVA) require multiple insertion attempts. Ultrasound‐guided PIVC insertion has been proposed as an alternative to standard (palpation and visualisation) technique, but its effectiveness has not been evaluated in clinical practice. Methods: A pragmatic randomised controlled superiority trial of children requiring insertion of a PIVC at a quaternary paediatric hospital, Brisbane, Australia. Children were included if aged term‐neonate‐18 years, having a PIVC inserted whilst self‐ventilating. Children were randomly allocated (1:1 ratio) to standard or ultrasound‐guided PIVC insertion, stratified by DIVA key (perceived degree of difficulty‐see figure 1) using a web‐based randomisation service. One device per patient was studied. The primary outcome was first time insertion success. Secondary outcomes included total number of PIVC insertion attempts, PIVC‐insertion failure, postinsertion complications, dwell time, patient/parent satisfaction, and healthcare costs. The trial was registered with Australia New Zealand Clinical Trials Registry, ACTRN12621000206820. Results: Between (July 2021‐December 2022) 164 children were randomly allocated, 84 to standard care, and 84 to USG PIVC insertion. Primary outcome data were collected for 164 (100%) participants, all of whom were included in the intention to treat analysis. First time insertion success was higher in USG‐PIVCs (72 [85.7%] compared to standard technique 26 [32.5%]); risk difference (RD) 53.2; 95% confidence interval (CI) 40.5‐65.9; p=<0.001). USG‐PIVC insertion was associated with fewer insertion attempts (median difference (MD)‐1.0 (‐1.4‐0.6); <0.001), greater mean patient/parent satisfaction (9.5 vs 5.6 out of 10; mean difference 4.0; 95% CI 3.1‐4.9; p = 0.002) with insertion, however no difference detected in overall PIVC failure, post insertion complications or dwell‐time. Conclusion: Use of USG for PIVC insertion improved first time PIVC insertion success as well as increased overall patient and parent satisfaction.
