TY  - JOUR
TI  - The utility of peripheral intravenous catheters inserted in the emergency department and their survivorship in the hospital
AU  - Shokoohi, H
AU  - Boniface, K
AU  - Kulie, P
AU  - Long, A
AU  - McCarthy, ML
JO  - Academic emergency medicine
AB  - Objective: To determine the utilization and survivorship rates of peripheral intravenous (IV) catheters inserted in the emergency department (ED). Methods: We analyzed 1,174 ED patients randomly assigned to ultrasound'guided or landmark peripheral catheter insertion. Research Assistants (RAs) recorded the uses of the ED‐inserted catheters during the ED visit and hospitalization, if admitted. Among subjects admitted, RAs prospectively tracked catheter survivorship for up to 72 hours or hospital discharge. RAs documented the date and time of catheter removal, whether the catheter was replaced and reason for removal. The main outcomes were the number of different uses of the ED‐inserted catheters in the ED and hospital and rate of premature removal among the admitted subjects. We used multivariate logistic regression to identify factors associated with premature removal and Kaplan‐Meier to compare survivorship duration by insertion method. Results: Ultrasound‐guided catheter insertion was used for more than half of the overall (53%) and admitted (55%) samples. The catheter utilization was 73% and 78% in the ED and hospital for the administration of fluids, medications or contrast agents (and 96% if blood draws were included). Among the 330 admitted subjects, 75% of the ED‐placed IVs survived until completion of care or 72 hours. There was no significant difference in catheter survivorship by insertion method. Conclusion: ED‐inserted peripheral IV catheters were frequently used for multiple diagnostic and treatment applications both in the ED and hospital. Ultrasound‐guided catheter insertion did not negatively impact survivorship among ED patients with varying levels of difficulty of IV access.
